data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt` calls to replace.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort): You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` + `Task.WhenAll`, which would also give you `CancellationToken` support for free if you need it later:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
    CancellationToken token = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, token, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        await Task.Delay(100, ct); // replaces Thread.Sleep
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

But again — this is purely optional. Your existing code requires zero changes for .NET 8.
